I used the 68HCS12 microcontroller for school in a Embedded Systems class and I wanted an EVB to play around with. The HCS12 is pretty easy to work with if you can keep the registers in order (in your head) It has many of the features you might need like I/O compare, ADC, Timer, (I use these the most).. The board comes with an bread board attachment which can be handy. When it came it looked brand new straight from Axion. I bought an serial to USB cable from "plugable" which I would recommend if your laptop does not have D9 port. I installed the Serial to USB driver. Hooked up the EVB. Installed HCS12 compiler and loader. Found the Serial Channel and loaded a program in the CD and it was running in about 15 minutes. So I know it works of of basic programs. I am looking into getting Codewarrior for HCS12. They do have code size restriuctions which I think is kind of dirty but there are ways around it. It would help programming the Chip(writing in Assembly is hell). Make sure you read the data sheet of freescale to see if the chip works for your needs. This chip only has 4K EEPROM memory 512K Byte Flash, EEPROM 14K Byte SRAM, which I think is enough for programming a cheap robot to detect landmines. Great buy for 20 bucks. get plugable serial to USB..It works great too.. Happy Engineering
